sed organizations they founded came to pursue a very different goal: a neighborhood with national retailers and increasingly affluent residents. The Roots of Urban Renaissance demonstrates that gentrification was not imposed on an unwitting community by unscrupulous developers or opportunistic outsiders. Rather, it grew from the neighborhood’s grassroots, producing a legacy that benefited some longtime residents and threatened others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aArchitects' Renewal Committee in Harlem.  aHarlem Commonwealth Council.  aHarlem Urban Development.  aJ. Max Bond.  aMorningside Heights.  aPreservation of the East Harlem Triangle.  abrownstones.  acommercial development.  agentrification.  ahousing abandonment.  alow-income housing.  amodel cities.  anew york state affordable housing.  aurban homesteading.  aurban renewal.1 aSugrue, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074973140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691243474?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691243474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691243474/original  a978-3-11-074973-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK